Maybe the else should return an empty QIcon plus some [warning](https://docs.python.org/2/library/warnings.html#warnings.warn)?

```
else:
   warning.warn('You need to have a running QApplication to use QtAwesome!')
   return QIcon()
```

`'function'` scope is the default and doesn't have to be specified.  Makes for slightly cleaner looking fixtures.

```python
@pytest.fixture
def thing(...):
    ...
```

The command-line format should be like tags or metadata: i.e `a=b c=d`. Space-separated key values pairs, not comma or semi-colon separated. You would basically use a validator that looks like this (pulled from Network):

```Python
def validate_metadata(namespace):
    if namespace.metadata:
        namespace.metadata = dict(x.split('=', 1) for x in namespace.metadata)
```

But thanks for pointing this out as you helped me recall the reason why I need the two lines:
if registry_from_name:
source_registry = registry_from_name.id

